1. Preface

Main purpose of shiny package is to support communication, presentation and data visualisation. Shiny allows to interactively change parameters of the code and perform computations of certain procedures with graphical interface. The role of the package is clearly presented on following scheme:

Of course business practice found various different applications of shiny tools:

  • analitycal dashboards,
  • interactive web application,
  • designing prototypes of application (before development phase),
  • GUI for statistical models and R packages (for researchers and other users),

Letâ€™s find out how it work. For inspiration visit shiny gallery.

2.First steps

2.1. Package installation

Shiny application are available in shiny package. In newer version of RStudio you do not need to import this package manually in order to run shiny app.

install.packages('shiny')

2.2. Architecture of shiny apps

Shiny applications works, exchanging information between ui (user interface) and server (where all of the computation are made). Relationship between them can be ilustrated with below scheme1:

role of ui.R:

  • enable to input data by user, mainly with widgets,
  • display output of the server engine
  • organise user interface (layout, appearence - frontend of the app)

roll of the server.R

  • receiving input,
  • carrying computation,
  • returning output.

2.3. Basic architecture of ui and server

ui.R

fluidPage()

server.R

function(input, output) {}

Letâ€™s create such files in R and try to launch application using methods described below.

2.4. How to run shiny app?

Method 1. Primary wat is to click on button:

Method 2. Another way is to call runApp function:

shiny::runApp(appDir='path_to_location_with_app_files', launch.browser = TRUE/FALSE)

Method 3. If both components are placed in one file (usually called app.R) and ui and server functions are assigned to objects ui and server, like this:

ui <- fluidPage()

server <- function(input, output)

we can use shinyApp function:

shiny::shinyApp(ui, server)

From now on, please copy each example and try to launch it RStudio.

3. Podstawy interfejsu graficznego

3.1. Title panel

Title panel is created with function titlePanel() used as argumeng of fluidPage():

ui.R

fluidPage(

  titlePanel("This is title!")
  
)

If we know HTML and css, we can easily introduce some formatting:

ui.R

fluidPage(

  div(titlePanel("This is title!"), style="background-color: #e6f2ff;")
  
)

3.2. pasek boczny i pasek gÅ‚Ã³wny.

Czyli dodajemy dwa panele: panel boczny i panel gÅ‚Ã³wny. Tworzymy je umieszczajÄ…c w funkcji sidebarLayout, dwie funkcje otwierajÄ…ce: sidebarPanel i mainPanel.

ui.R

fluidPage(

  titlePanel("This is title!"),

  sidebarLayout(

    sidebarPanel(
        # here widgets are placed
    ),

    mainPanel(
        # here graphs and table are displayed
    )
  )
)

Sidebar can be rearrange on right hand side of app.s

ui.R

fluidPage(

  titlePanel("This is title!"),

  sidebarLayout(position="right",

    sidebarPanel(
        # here widgets are placed
    ),

    mainPanel(
        # here graphs and table are displayed
    )
  )
)

4. Case study: k-means visualisation of Iris dataset

ui.R

pageWithSidebar(
  headerPanel('Iris k-means clustering'),
  sidebarPanel(
    selectInput('xcol', 'X Variable', names(iris)),
    selectInput('ycol', 'Y Variable', names(iris),
                selected=names(iris)[[2]]),
    numericInput('clusters', 'Cluster count', 3,
                 min = 1, max = 9)
  ),
  mainPanel(
    plotOutput('plot1')
  )
)

server.R

function(input, output, session) {

  # Combine the selected variables into a new data frame
  selectedData <- reactive({
    iris[, c(input$xcol, input$ycol)]
  })

  clusters <- reactive({
    kmeans(selectedData(), input$clusters)
  })

  output$plot1 <- renderPlot({
    palette(c("#E41A1C", "#377EB8", "#4DAF4A", "#984EA3",
      "#FF7F00", "#FFFF33", "#A65628", "#F781BF", "#999999"))

    par(mar = c(5.1, 4.1, 0, 1))
    plot(selectedData(),
         col = clusters()$cluster,
         pch = 20, cex = 3)
    points(clusters()$centers, pch = 4, cex = 4, lwd = 4)
  })

}

5. Hints for begginners

Almost every application demanded importing external packages and dataset to work. Letâ€™s find out how to this effectively in shiny architecture. Basically if you decide to create one app.R file, you should put at the top of the sript expressions like:

library('package')
source('path/to/external/source.R')
source('scripts/helpers.R')

dataset <- readRDS('data/data.rds')
load('data.Rdata)

If there are separate ui.R and server.R import of libraries and datasets is usually placed in server file, however sometimses user interface needs some data at launch, so necessary commands has to be put there as well.
